From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] drivers/ps4: v19 - ICC polling fallback

v18 diagnostics confirmed:
  STATUS=0x3 (SEND|ACK both set) at every timeout
  IRQ_MASK=0x3 (IRQs enabled)
  REPLY full=1 (reply data is in SPM)
  icc_interrupt never gets called (no entry log)

So the mailbox HW works perfectly -- the southbridge processes our
request, writes the reply to SPM, sets STATUS bits.  But the MSI
to fire icc_interrupt never reaches our handler.  Will diagnose
the MSI delivery issue separately.

Workaround: poll STATUS register from process context after issuing
each request.  When STATUS shows an event, manually invoke
icc_interrupt(0, sc) -- it does the right thing whether called from
IRQ or process context.

Also clears stale STATUS bits before each request.  The southbridge
seems not to raise a fresh edge if the previous bits are still
pending unack'd (we missed the IRQ for the prior command).

Cost: ~500us-1ms latency per ICC command (vs the HZ*ICC_TIMEOUT
wait that previously always failed).  A handful of ICC commands
per boot, so wall-clock cost is negligible.

Note: the existing ICC_TIMEOUT macro has a trailing-semicolon bug
("#define ICC_TIMEOUT 15;") that breaks expression-context use.
Hardcoded 15 in the new poll loop.

If v19 works:
- "Turn ON BT/WLAN" returns 0 with a real reply
- icc_pwrbutton_init succeeds
- ps4_bridge can talk to the HDMI bridge chip
- HDMI display comes up

---
--- a/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie-icc.c
+++ b/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie-icc.c
@@ -227,14 +227,36 @@
 	sc->icc.reply_pending = true;
 	spin_unlock_irq(&sc->icc.reply_lock);
 
+	/* v19: clear any stale STATUS bits left over from a missed IRQ on a
+	 * previous command, otherwise the southbridge may not raise a fresh
+	 * IRQ for this request. */
+	iowrite32(BPCIE_ICC_SEND | BPCIE_ICC_ACK,
+		  sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_STATUS);
+
 	iowrite32(BPCIE_ICC_SEND, sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_DOORBELL);
 
-	if (intr)
-		ret = wait_event_interruptible_timeout(sc->icc.wq,
-				!sc->icc.reply_pending, HZ * ICC_TIMEOUT);
-	else
-		ret = wait_event_timeout(sc->icc.wq,
-				!sc->icc.reply_pending, HZ * ICC_TIMEOUT);
+	/* v19: POLL fallback.  Confirmed in v18 that the southbridge sets
+	 * STATUS=0x3 + REPLY full=1 but the IRQ never fires (icc_interrupt
+	 * never gets called).  Until we resolve the MSI delivery, poll the
+	 * STATUS register every ~1ms and run the handler manually when an
+	 * event appears.  Caps at HZ * ICC_TIMEOUT total wait. */
+	{
+		/* hardcode 15s — ICC_TIMEOUT macro has a trailing ; bug (it
+		 * expands to "15;" which is invalid inside an expression). */
+		unsigned long deadline = jiffies + HZ * 15;
+		ret = 0;
+		while (time_before(jiffies, deadline)) {
+			u32 st = ioread32(sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_STATUS);
+			if (st & (BPCIE_ICC_SEND | BPCIE_ICC_ACK)) {
+				icc_interrupt(0, sc);
+			}
+			if (!READ_ONCE(sc->icc.reply_pending)) {
+				ret = 1;
+				break;
+			}
+			usleep_range(500, 1000);
+		}
+	}
 
 	spin_lock_irq(&sc->icc.reply_lock);
 	sc->icc.reply_buffer = NULL;
